(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(appendix
  :book                "Book of Narrative Games"
  :letter              "E"
  :title               "Fade, Dim, Curtain — the Physics of Transition"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :G
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :prose
"Transitions are punctuation. A hard cut is a period. A fade is an
ellipsis. A dim is a semicolon. A curtain is a chapter break. Each has
a specific job. This appendix shows when to use which.

The verbs: surface/dim, surface/curtain, surface/spotlight,
surface/paper, and the compound patterns built from them.

---

## surface/dim

Reduce the surface brightness to a given level over N frames.

```scheme
(surface/dim 0.5 20)     ;; dim to 50% brightness over 20 frames
(surface/dim 0.0 60)     ;; fade to black over 60 frames (1 second)
(surface/dim 1.0 30)     ;; fade back to full over 30 frames
```

Level 0.0 is black. Level 1.0 is full brightness. Anything between is
partial.

- **0.9 or 0.85** — barely noticeable dim. Useful for a moment of
  hesitation.
- **0.5** — clearly dimmed. The scene is transitioning; something
  is ending.
- **0.2 or 0.1** — deep dim. About to cut.
- **0.0** — full black. Chapter break, sleep, death.

Duration:
- **10-15 frames** (quick) — an unease pulse.
- **20-30 frames** (moderate) — a normal scene transition.
- **60+ frames** (slow) — solemn, weighty.

---

## surface/curtain

A soft close, as if a stage curtain is coming down. Different from
dim — dim reduces brightness; curtain draws in from the edges.

```scheme
(surface/curtain :duration 60)      ;; curtain in over 1 second
```

Use for chapter endings, for the moment a big scene closes, for the
game's final frame.

Screenplay analog: FADE TO BLACK versus THE CURTAIN FALLS.

---

## surface/paper

Sets the surface to a warm paper-colored background. The opposite of
dim — establishes a fresh, welcoming page.

```scheme
(surface/paper)      ;; warm off-white background
```

Call at the start of every scene, right after `scene/imagine`. The
combination is your standard scene-opening.

```scheme
(scene/imagine)
(surface/paper)
;; now paint your text
```

---

## surface/spotlight

Draws attention to a specific screen region.

```scheme
(surface/spotlight x y width height :duration 90 :color 'soft-yellow)
```

The region gets a soft glow; everything outside dims slightly. Use
sparingly — the equivalent of italic emphasis in prose.

Good uses:
- A word in a poem the reader should linger on.
- A specific object in a scene the audience should notice.
- A choice option that is the recommended path.

Bad uses:
- Marking every important item (loses meaning).
- Following the mouse (annoying).

---

## surface/dusk

A gradient tint applied to the whole surface — warmer at the top,
cooler at the bottom, mimicking the color shift of late-afternoon
light.

```scheme
(surface/dusk)      ;; the whole scene takes on a golden lower-blue upper cast
```

Use for late-afternoon scenes, autumn scenes, endings. It sets a
mood without changing content.

---

## Compound patterns

Scene transitions typically compose two or three primitives.

### Fade out, cut, fade in

```scheme
(define (fade-out-then-in next-scene)
  (surface/dim 0.0 30)            ;; fade to black over half a second
  (world/after 30
    (lambda ()
      (scene/imagine)              ;; clear
      (surface/paper)              ;; reset to paper
      (next-scene)                 ;; run next scene
      (surface/dim 1.0 30))))      ;; fade up over half a second
```

Standard scene-to-scene transition. Familiar to any film-viewer.

### Dim-freeze

```scheme
(define (dim-freeze)
  (surface/dim 0.5 15)             ;; quick dim
  (world/after 60                  ;; hold for 1 second
    (lambda ()
      (surface/dim 1.0 15))))      ;; restore
```

The scene dims briefly and comes back. Signals a beat of hesitation
— a character remembers something, has second thoughts, catches
their breath.

### The chapter break

```scheme
(define (chapter-break n title)
  (audio/halt)
  (surface/dim 0.0 60)             ;; slow fade to black
  (world/after 60
    (lambda ()
      (scene/imagine)
      (paint-text 300 240 (string-append \"~ \" (number->string n) \" ~\"))
      (paint-text 300 280 title)
      (surface/dim 1.0 45)          ;; fade in title
      (world/after 180              ;; hold for 3 seconds
        (lambda ()
          (surface/dim 0.0 60)      ;; fade out title
          (world/after 60
            (lambda ()
              (scene/imagine)
              (surface/paper)
              (start-chapter n)))))))))
```

Six seconds. Fade to black, silence, title appears, hold, title fades,
next chapter begins.

### The wake-up

The character was unconscious. Now the scene fades in from black.

```scheme
(define (wake-up)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/dim 0.0 0)              ;; start black
  (paint-text 40 300 \"...\")        ;; text appears while still dim
  (world/after 30
    (lambda () (surface/dim 0.3 90)))  ;; slowly brighten
  (world/after 150
    (lambda () (surface/dim 0.7 90)))
  (world/after 270
    (lambda () (surface/dim 1.0 90))
    (paint-text 40 350 \"...you are on the floor. Your head hurts.\")))
```

Three-stage fade-up, mimicking the return of consciousness. The
audience feels the character wake up.

### The dream sequence

```scheme
(define (dream-start)
  (surface/dim 0.6 30)             ;; muted brightness
  (audio/play 'dream-drone :loop? #t :volume 0.2)   ;; ambient shift
  (surface/spotlight 200 200 300 200 :duration 300))  ;; soft focus in the middle

(define (dream-end)
  (audio/halt 'dream-drone)
  (surface/dim 1.0 30)             ;; brightness returns
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper))                   ;; back to normal page
```

The dream starts with a soft dim + drone + spotlight. Content plays
in the spotlit region. Dream ends with a restore.

### The death fade

```scheme
(define (character-dies)
  (audio/halt)
  (surface/dim 0.0 240)            ;; slow four-second fade to black
  (world/after 240
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 300 300 \"[end]\")
      (world/after 180
        (lambda () (credits))))))
```

Four seconds of fade. Total silence. Then a single word: [end]. Then
credits.

Use once per game. This is the strongest transition you have.

---

## What NOT to do

**Do not fade during a dialogue line.** The reader is trying to read.
Fading the surface makes the text hard to see. Complete the fade
BEFORE painting text or AFTER the text has been read.

**Do not spotlight every important thing.** If everything is
spotlit, nothing is. Reserve spotlight for the moment the audience
must not miss.

**Do not use dim to signal 'you can interact.'** Some game designers
use dim to indicate 'this UI element is active.' In narrative games,
dim means emotional weight, not UI state.

**Do not use curtain more than three times per game.** It is a
capital-C Curtain. Reserve for act breaks and the final scene.

---

## Speed reference

At 60 frames per second:

- 5 frames = 0.08 seconds (a blink)
- 15 frames = 0.25 seconds (quick)
- 30 frames = 0.5 seconds (moderate)
- 60 frames = 1 second (deliberate)
- 90 frames = 1.5 seconds (slow)
- 180 frames = 3 seconds (very slow — reserve for big moments)
- 240 frames = 4 seconds (glacial — reserve for endings)

---

## Summary

Dim for weight. Curtain for closure. Paper for opening. Spotlight
for emphasis. Dusk for mood.

Compound primitives to build fade-out-fade-in, chapter breaks,
wake-ups, dreams, deaths.

Every transition is punctuation. Choose your punctuation the way you
choose your words: with intent.")
